title: For Sale:  McCabe’s Custom Leather IWB Holster for S&W BodyGuard 380 w/Laser
postcontent:
Need a custom made IWB holster for your Smith & Wesson Bodyguard 380 with Laser?

I have some leather holsters designed by some of the absolute top craftsman in the holster business. Made from the best hides and cut with great attention to detail. But even these high dollar holsters can feel rigid and unforgiving at times due to the thickness of the leather. 

Kydex has some advantages over leather in that can be thin and yet very durable and weather resistant. It can be shaped to just about any form and for an outside the waistband application, it can be a perfect solution, especially where it will be exposed to foul weather. 
But Kydex can sometimes feel harsh when worn inside the waistband under a t-shirt against your body. It's that feeling of metal or plastic against your skin that can annoy over time. For me, outside the waistband in the elements is ok; inside against your skin, no so much. With that said, I do currently have a particular Kydex holster that's on my wish list right now, but it won't be against my skin. 

Nylon can be very comfortable and very affordable. I have some nylon holsters and I like them for their small size and comfortable feeling, not to mention their cost effectiveness. But they can lack a certain confident feeling of pistol management. It always seems to feel like a bag rather than a fitted holster. Again, I have several and use one for inside the front pocket in Jeans for its small size and comfortable characteristics, and it's a favorite for that application.

But no holster is perfect and a year ago, I was in the market for a holster for a new Smith & Wesson Bodyguard 380. I liked the small size of the BG380 and believed it would conceal well in an inside the waistband application that would be against my body in summer months under a T-shirt. 

At the time, I was fortunate enough to read an article about Billy McCabe of McCabes's Custom Leather. I was interested enough to order three IWB holsters for the new BG380 with laser. 

McCabe created an IWB holster that seems to address everything I wanted in this holster. It is a perfectly shaped leather holster that is thin enough to address comfort and yet thick enough to address pistol management. The finish is a matte black as opposed to the more often seen shinny or glossy look.

The leather is also thin enough to avoid feeling hard or rigid. My first thought was that it reminded me of Italian leather because it's a little thinner than most. If you want a holster that will take a year to break in and that you will pass down to your grandchildren, this is probably not the holster for you. If you want a holster that will be comfortable from day one, this may very well be your next holster. (Besides, your grand kids will most likely be using Apple's new I-ZapU, an implanted 1000-TB pulverizing cloud weapon anyway.)  

The fit is perfect, including an extended rise in the back of the leather to keep the slide off my skin. (See photo) All in all a very simple and clean design that perfectly matches my BG380 - Very simple, just leather and craftsmanship. It just looks right for the BG380. And after living with it for a while, it is right - for my needs. It's so right, I wondered if that's what Billy carries.

I would love to ask him to make me a custom front pocket holster for a little Seecamp but he is backed up for months and currently not taking any new orders - none. That brings me to the point of all of this. 

I ordered three holsters from Billy when he was still taking orders and I waited about five months for mine. But I do have one extra McCabes custom-made IWB all black leather holster for a SW BG380 with laser. (See photos) So if you are in the market for one, I may have just what you want without the waiting. It’s never been used or worn and it's just $100, plus $12 s/h.

postcontent:
Complete Hammerli 160 with accessories and case, except no OEM manual.

This gun is one of several target and "other use" pistols available, which are NOT listed on Armslist.  For a complete list and EXPERT'S SELECTION GUIDE to these guns, please email.  The guide and list are free.  The guide covers a wide range of target and other use pistols by Hammerli, Walther, SIG-Hammerli, Steyr, Pfuff, Hi Standard, and S&W (M41).  A second guide (and list of to be sold items) includes rifles by Walther, Anschutz, Tanner, Gruenig and Elmiger, Schultz and Larsen in .22 and center fire calibers.  These are free for the asking.

Includes all (I think) tools, and full set of weights. OEM case marked Hammerli, and original test target (pictured).

$1870, offers considered. FFL transfer only.

The gun really is not as accurate as the target would suggest. Hammerli was not entirely honest with the test targets of the 100 and 200 series guns, and slanted the data towards greater accuracy due to the testing method used.

That said, the gun is more accurate than the current Morini and Pardini series, probably better than the TOZ35 or at least as accurate, but not as accurate as the Steyr and Pfuff free pistols by 20 rounds fired.

The 160 uses a higher barrel position than the Steyr and Pfuff, so it does not require the high sight position for those positions, and is not as sensitive to hand position in the grip when shooting.

The 160 is similar to the 150, but the cartridge exraction is less fussy, and the trigger is a bit improved. Both are significantly smoother than the 120, which uses a Luger locking system rather than a falling or rotating block.

The gun is in near perfect condition. The OEM and SN matched case has a few marks, but is at least in very good condition. Please remember, the materials for the case and tools OEM Hammerli are cheap, and their quality does not parallel the guns.

$1870 but offers considered, as there is not much info for basing a price on this gun.

If desired, 120, 150, Steyr, and Pfuff Match free pistols also are available. The Steyr begins in this price range, the others are less.

Again, this gun is one of several target and "other use" pistols available, which are NOT listed on Armslist.  For a complete list and EXPERT'S SELECTION GUIDE to these guns, please email.  The guide and list are free.

title: For Sale:  *** SOLD *** Smith & Wesson Bodyguard BG 380 IWB Holster
postcontent:
Need a custom made IWB holster for your Smith & Wesson Bodyguard 380 with Laser? 

A year ago, I was in the market for a holster for a new Smith & Wesson Bodyguard 380. I liked the small size of the BG380 and believed it would conceal well in an inside the waistband application that would be against my body in summer months under a T-shirt. 

At the time, I was fortunate enough to read an article about Billy McCabe of McCabes's Custom Leather. I was interested enough to order three IWB holsters for the new BG380 with laser. 

McCabe created an IWB holster that seems to address everything I wanted in this holster. It is a perfectly shaped leather holster that is thin enough to address comfort and yet thick enough to address pistol management. The finish is a matte black as opposed to the more often seen shinny or glossy look.

The leather is also thin enough to avoid feeling hard or rigid. My first thought was that it reminded me of Italian leather because it's a little thinner than most. If you want a holster that will take a year to break in and that you will pass down to your grandchildren, this is probably not the holster for you. If you want a holster that will be comfortable from day one, this may very well be your next holster. (Besides, your grand kids will most likely be using Apple's new I-ZapU, an implanted 1000-TB pulverizing cloud weapon anyway.)  

The fit is perfect, including an extended rise in the back of the leather to keep the slide off my skin. (See photo) All in all a very simple and clean design that perfectly matches my BG380 - Very simple, just leather and craftsmanship. It just looks right for the BG380. And after living with it for a while, it is right - for my needs. It's so right, I wondered if that's what Billy carries.

I would love to ask him to make me a custom front pocket holster for a little Seecamp but he is backed up for months and currently not taking any new orders - none. That brings me to the point of all of this. 

I ordered three holsters from Billy when he was still taking orders and I waited about six months for mine. I do have one extra McCabes custom-made IWB all black leather holster for a SW BG380 with laser. (See photos) 

So if you are in the market for one, I may have just what you want without the waiting. It’s never been used or worn and it's just $75, shipping included.

title: Want To Buy:  AK/AR parts, mags, rifles
postcontent:
Looking for parts and rifles in the AR/AK family. Going to be rather blunt and to the point. 

First, if you have something, details are key, the more I know the better idea I have if it is worth my time, or something that I am looking for. Otherwise be prepared to get a laundry list of questions as a reply. I also need a price. No price or value and I am not liking going to bother responding. 

Only interested in 5.56 in ARs, and 7,62X39 for AKs. If you refuse to allow the rifle to be broken down for inspection do not offer it, I will assume you are trying to hide something and more on. If you don't know how to break it down, then we can talk. Will consider AR lowers, depending on condition, make, and parts used. Not interested in franken-ARs. And no, your DPMS is not built better than a Colt, nor would it be worth more, so don't try selling me your Sportical for $1200. As far as AKs, WASRs are not $900 rifles, and this isn't Haji-stan where if the rifle is beat to hell it gives street cred. Looking for quality rifles, not interested in Norinco, collectors pieces, or Century junk builds. 

As far as mags go not interested in mags that have beat up, been painted, are from unknown manufactuers, korean junk, pro mag, tapco, or their related failings. Also not interested in USGI or Magpul mags at 2X what I can order them for new. Also, not going to pay new price on used mags. 

Other things of interest. Quality mounts, rails, optics, lights. Need another Scout light, maybe two, as well as several other things. Again, UTG, promag, and related junk is not of interest. 

Not interested in ammo unless the price is cheap and below what I can buy it for. And no Cabela's prices are not good so don't use that as a reference. 

Lastly, don't waste my time with BS offers, bait and switch, overpriced junk, or if you think your stuff is worth five times more than you paid for it. You know who you are.

Looking for local, and local only.
